If $\left|\frac{12}{x}+3\right|=2$, find the product of all possible values of $x$. Express your answer as an improper fraction. ||| We can split the expression $\left|\frac{12}{x}+3\right|=2$ into two separate cases. In the first case, we have 
\begin{align*} 
\frac{12}{x}+3&=2 \\
\Rightarrow \qquad \frac{12}{x}&=5 \\
\Rightarrow \qquad 12&=5x \\
\Rightarrow \qquad x&=\frac{12}{5} 
\end{align*}In the second case, 
\begin{align*} 
\frac{12}{x}+3&=-2 \\
\Rightarrow \qquad \frac{12}{x}&=-5 \\
\Rightarrow \qquad 12&=-5x \\
\Rightarrow \qquad x&=\frac{-12}{5} 
\end{align*}The product of all possible values of $x$ is equal to $\left(\frac{12}{5}\right)(\frac{-12}{5})=\boxed{-\frac{144}{25}}$.

