Larry writes the number 3 on his pinky finger.  He then applies $f$ to 3 and writes the output on his ring finger.  If Larry continues this process of applying $f$ and writing the output on a new finger, what number will Larry write on his tenth finger? ||| Starting with 3 on his pinky, Larry finds $f(3)=8$, so he writes 8 on his second finger. Continuing, he applies $f$ again and sees that $f(8)=7$, which goes on his third finger. Then he finds $f(7)=6$ and writes that on his fourth finger. After that, $f(6)=5$, leading to writing 5 on his fifth finger. He continues applying $f$ and sees $f(5)=4$, which goes on his sixth finger. Eventually, he calculates that $f(4)=2$, so he writes 2 on his seventh finger. Upon applying $f$ once more, he writes $f(2)=1$ on his eighth finger. Finally, applying $f(1)=3$ leads to writing 3 on his ninth finger. Finally, applying $f$ for the tenth time gives $f(3)=8$. Thus, Larry writes \boxed{8} on his tenth finger.
